\f0\fs56 \cf2 \kerning1\expnd-2\expndtw-10
\up0 \nosupersub \ulnone PICO AUDIO I2S\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs22 \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 There are several factors that are key to producing high quality audio with the Raspberry Pi Pico.\
\pard\tx360\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2 \cf2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone Clocks with accurate frequencies, phase relationships and low jitter.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone Good board layout.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone Input and output filtering.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 While many tutorials on Pico I2S focus only on output through a DAC or I2S amplifier IC, here we will also deal with signal input using audio CODECs.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\b\fs36 \cf2 Clocks\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf2 Design constraints:\
\pard\tx360\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2 \cf2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone Accurate clock frequencies ensure that the pitch of the captured or produced sound are as expected.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone Clock jitter must be minimised, and hopefully eliminated, to minimise distortion of the audio signal.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone Correct phase relationships between the various clock signals, namely MCLK, BCLK (SCLK) and LRCLK (WCLK) must be maintained.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone Some DACs and CODECs do not require MCLK, as they contain internal PLLs that can generate the signal.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone Other system functions (e.g. USB) must not be disturbed by adjusting the RP2040 clocking to generate I2S signals.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\b\fs28 \cf2 Jitter \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf2 Jitter needs to be addressed at two levels \'96 the RP2040 sys_clk frequency needs to have the lowest possible jitter, as well as the MCLK and BCLK signals created by the PIO clock dividers and code.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs16 \cf3 [sys_clk] Jitter is minimised by running the VCO at the highest possible frequency, so that higher post-divide values can be used. (DS 230)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs22 \cf2 For the PIO clock dividers \cb4 it is best that the integer divisor be an even number\cb1  and the fractional part should be zero, as other values will introduce unacceptable clock jitter from the delta-sigma fractional divider, particularly at low fractional values.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li207\ri567\sa120\qc\partightenfactor0

\f3\b \cf5 ??? Should the sys_clk and PIO divisors also be a power of 2????\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sl259\slmult1\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs16 \cf3 The [PIO] clock dividers are 16-bit integer, 8-bit fractional, with first-order delta-sigma for the fractional divider. The clock divisor can vary between 1 and 65536, in increments of 1/256. 
\f1\fs22 \cf2 \'85\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs16 \cf3 For small 
\f5\i \cf3 n
\f4\i0 \cf3 , the jitter introduced by a fractional divider may be unacceptable. However, for larger values, this effect is much less apparent (DS 338)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs22 \cf2 For the lowest possible jitter, as many of the dividers as possible should have divisors that are powers of two (1, 2, 4,8, etc). This applies most importantly to dividers close to the signal output, as jitter from dividers further up the chain tends to be evened out by the following dividers. \
Ultimately, a balance needs to be struck between reducing jitter and finding achievable VCO and sys_clk frequencies.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\b\fs28 \cf2 Frequency\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf2 Finding an appropriate sys_clk frequency for each of the required MCLK frequencies is not a trivial exercise given all the constraints, outlined above. \
\
To avoid clock jitter \
\pard\tx360\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f2 \cf2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone sys_clk to PIO clock divisors for MCLK / BCLK should be integral and even numbers. \uc0\u8232 As MCLK is always an even, integral multiplier of BCLK, constraining MCLK is sufficient to ensure an appropriate BCLK divisor.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone While sys_clk should preferably be an even (or, even better, a power of 2) divisor of the VCO frequency (particularly the POSTDIV2 value), this may prove to be an unachievable constraint.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0

\f6\fs14 \cf6 FOUTPOSTDIV 
\f4\fs16 \cf3 can then be calculated as (
\f6\fs14 \cf6 FREF 
\f4\fs16 \cf3 / 
\f6\fs14 \cf6 REFDIV
\f4\fs16 \cf3 ) \'d7 
\f6\fs14 \cf6 FBDIV 
\f4\fs16 \cf3 / (
\f6\fs14 \cf6 POSTDIV1 
\f4\fs16 \cf3 \'d7 
\f6\fs14 \cf6 POSTDIV2
\f4\fs16 \cf3 ). With a desired output frequency in mind, you must select PLL parameters according to the following constraints of the PLL design:\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0

\f7\fs28 \cf3 \'95
\f4 \cf3  
\fs16 \cf3 Minimum reference frequency (
\f6\fs14 \cf6 FREF 
\f4\fs16 \cf3 / 
\f6\fs14 \cf6 REFDIV
\f4\fs16 \cf3 ) is 5MHz\

\f7\fs28 \cf3 \'95
\f4 \cf3  
\fs16 \cf3 Oscillator frequency (
\f6\fs14 \cf6 FOUTVCO
\f4\fs16 \cf3 ) must be in the range 750MHz 
\f6 \cf3 \'81\'a8 
\f4 \cf3 1600MHz\

\f7\fs28 \cf3 \'95
\f4 \cf3  
\fs16 \cf3 Feedback divider (
\f6\fs14 \cf6 FBDIV
\f4\fs16 \cf3 ) must be in the range 16 
\f6 \cf3 \'81\'a8 
\f4 \cf3 320\

\f7\fs28 \cf3 \'95
\f4 \cf3  
\fs16 \cf3 The post dividers 
\f6\fs14 \cf6 POSTDIV1 
\f4\fs16 \cf3 and 
\f6\fs14 \cf6 POSTDIV2 
\f4\fs16 \cf3 must be in the range 1 
\f6 \cf3 \'81\'a8 
\f4 \cf3 7\

\f7\fs28 \cf3 \'95
\f4 \cf3  
\fs16 \cf3 Maximum input frequency (
\f6\fs14 \cf6 FREF 
\f4\fs16 \cf3 / 
\f6\fs14 \cf6 REFDIV
\f4\fs16 \cf3 ) is VCO frequency divided by 16, due to minimum feedback divisor Additionally, the maximum frequencies of the chip\'92s clock generators (attached to 
\f6\fs14 \cf6 FOUTPOSTDIV
\f4\fs16 \cf3 ) must be respected. For the system PLL this is 133MHz, and for the USB PLL, 48MHz.\
(DS 229)\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

